Tiered Fallback System

SmartPitch classifies the forecast for the 12 hours before each session into weather bands, then searches historical sessions for a match. If an exact 4-band match exists, it uses those parameters. Otherwise it progressively relaxes the match, dropping weather dimensions one at a time.

TIER 1 Exact Match — 4 bands
Temp + Cloud + Humidity + Wind all match. Best possible prediction from directly comparable sessions.
TIER 2 3-Band — drops humidity
Temp + Cloud + Wind. Humidity has the weakest correlation with frost outcomes so it is dropped first.
TIER 3 2-Band — temp + cloud only
The two most important factors: temperature determines frost severity, cloud cover determines radiative cooling rate.
TIER 4 Temp Only — 1 band + heat curve blend
Only temperature band matches. Learning data is broad, so the recommendation is averaged with the heat curve to keep it grounded in physics.
TIER 5 Global Average — all sessions + heat curve blend
No weather-specific match possible. Averages all historical sessions regardless of conditions. Blended with heat curve since global averages may not suit current weather.
FALLBACK Heat Curve Only — no learning data
Fewer than 3 sessions in the database. Uses the heat curve with soil-deficit adjustment until enough data is collected.

How Sessions Are Classified

1. The system takes the 12-hour forecast window before each session deadline and averages the temperature, cloud cover, humidity, and wind speed.
2. These averages are bucketed into weather bands (e.g. T-2..0, C0..10). See the Bands Reference tab for all thresholds.
3. The bands are matched against historical sessions to find what worked before in similar conditions — lead time, flow temperature, energy used, pass/fail rate.
4. The system uses the most energy-efficient parameters that still achieved a pass, progressively relaxing the match if no exact data exists.

Heat Curve Blending (TIER 4 & 5)

When the match quality is poor (TIER 4 or 5), the learning recommendation is averaged with the heat curve setpoint:

setpoint = (learning temp + heat curve temp) / 2

This prevents the system from blindly following a global average that may have been built from mild-weather sessions when facing a severe frost. The heat curve provides a physics-based sanity check.

Weather Band Definitions

Forecast values over the 12-hour window before each session are averaged and classified into these bands.

Temperature
T<=-6 \u2264 -6\u00b0C • Severe frost
T-6..-4 -6 to -4\u00b0C • Hard frost
T-4..-2 -4 to -2\u00b0C • Moderate frost
T-2..0 -2 to 0\u00b0C • Light frost
T0..2 0 to 2\u00b0C • Frost risk
T>2 > 2\u00b0C • Low risk
Cloud Cover
C0..10 < 10% • Clear sky
C10..30 10-30% • Mostly clear
C30..60 30-60% • Partial cloud
C60..85 60-85% • Mostly cloudy
C>85 \u2265 85% • Overcast
Humidity
H<60 < 60% • Dry
H60..80 60-80% • Moderate
H>80 \u2265 80% • High
Wind Speed
W0..2 < 2 m/s • Calm
W2..5 2-5 m/s • Light
W5..8 5-8 m/s • Moderate
W>8 \u2265 8 m/s • Strong

SmartPitch Mode

Learning-driven heating with slope-based safety net and learning optimization

Safety Net

The safety net is dormant by default. It monitors pitch temperature and only intervenes when the system is off-track or in emergency. Normal control comes from the heat curve and learning system.

WHEN SAFETY NET INTERVENES:
  • EMERGENCY — Pitch drops below emergency threshold
  • OFF-TRACK — Pitch falling too fast with deadline approaching
  • STALLED — No progress being made near deadline
  • SUCCESS — Can reduce heat once frost risk cleared (if safe)
Enable Safety Net Allow safety net to intervene when system is off-track
Emergency Threshold Pitch temp below which emergency intervention triggers
°C
Off-Track Slope Falling rate (°C/hr) that triggers off-track intervention
°C/hr
Evaluation Window Time window for calculating pitch temperature slope
min
Heat Curve Fallback

The heat curve provides baseline flow temperatures when learning data is insufficient. As the system learns, it relies less on this curve.

Use Heat Curve Enable heat curve as fallback when no learning data
Learning Confidence Threshold Minimum confidence before using learned data over heat curve
%

Soil Temperature Adjustments

Controls how soil temperature influences heating decisions. With learning data, the system compares current soil temp to the historical average and offsets setpoint/lead time. Without learning data, a thermal deficit calculation boosts heat when soil is cold.

WITH LEARNING DATA (soil offset):
  • Compares current soil temp to historical average at session start
  • Warmer soil = lower setpoint & later start. Colder = higher & earlier
Setpoint Factor Flow temp reduction per 1°C warmer soil vs historical average
°C/°C
Lead Time Factor Lead time reduction (hours) per 1°C warmer soil vs historical
hrs/°C
WITHOUT LEARNING DATA (thermal deficit):
  • When soil is below the threshold, boost flow temp and start earlier
  • Uses heat curve as base, adds deficit-based boost
Deficit Threshold Soil temp below which deficit boost activates
°C
Deficit Flow Boost Extra flow temp per 1°C of soil deficit
°C/°C
Deficit Lead Boost Extra lead time per 1°C of soil deficit
hrs/°C

Smart maintain heating between consecutive sessions. Instead of blindly holding a fixed temperature, the system reads the soil probe and decides the most energy-efficient action:

Decision priority (top to bottom):
1.Skip to ramp-up — If already within the learning lead time for the next session, jump straight to HEATING at the learned target temp. No point maintaining at 14°C when you need 18°C in 3 hours.
2.Soil safe — skip — If soil is well above safe threshold (+2°C), the pitch isn’t at risk. System monitors without heating.
3.Soil OK — reduced — If soil is above safe but not by much, maintain at a reduced temp (target − 2°C) to save energy while keeping a buffer.
4.Soil cold — full maintain — If soil is at or below safe threshold, maintain at the full configured temperature.
5.Beyond window — If the next session is further away than the maintain window, stop maintaining. The system will restart based on learning data.
Maintain Temperature Target flow temp between sessions
°C
Maintain Window How far ahead to look for next session
hours
Soil Safe Threshold Below this, soil is at frost risk (soil > safe+2°C = skip maintain)
°C
